    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:74f5535a-2b81-4d28-bc24-b5d14e191682",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 63-year-old woman who appears slightly older than her stated age, with a careful, composed manner that softens when she speaks about her family. She is neatly dressed, often in practical cardigans and walking shoes, and keeps a silk scarf in her handbag because she is often chilled in clinic waiting rooms. Over the past several months she has become more guarded with movement on the left side of her chest, occasionally touching the upper outer breast unconsciously when she is anxious. She reports a recently discovered breast lump and intermittent dull discomfort rather than severe pain, along with mounting fatigue and poor sleep driven more by worry than by physical symptoms.\n\nShe lives with her husband in a suburban neighborhood and works part-time as a librarian after cutting back from full-time employment a few years ago. Her days are structured and quiet: morning tea, a short walk with a neighbor, work at the library two or three days a week, and regular phone calls with her adult daughter. She enjoys gardening, historical novels, and attending a community choir, though she has recently skipped rehearsals because of medical appointments and emotional strain. She has never smoked, drinks wine only occasionally, and tries to eat sensibly, though her appetite has been inconsistent since learning she may have cancer.\n\nFriends describe {patientName} as dependable and private, someone who tends to care for others before herself. She delayed evaluation of the breast mass for several weeks because she did not want to alarm her family until she was sure something was wrong. Since the diagnosis workup began, she has become more tearful and distracted, but she remains engaged in her care and arrives with handwritten questions. She is independent in all activities of daily living and still drives herself locally.\n\nOn examination, she has a palpable irregular mass in the left breast with mild surrounding tenderness but no overlying skin breakdown. She is hemodynamically stable and not in acute distress. Her overall presentation is that of a functional older adult confronting a life-changing diagnosis, balancing fear, pragmatism, and a strong wish to remain active through treatment."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:e14aea70-f897-491e-aa17-cc2321c897c6",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has a history notable for postmenopausal status, hyperlipidemia, and well-controlled hypertension. She has not had prior malignancy and has never required hospitalization for major chronic illness, though she was admitted overnight several years ago after an uncomplicated breast biopsy observation period. She reports no tobacco use and only rare alcohol intake. Her BMI is mildly elevated, and she has become less physically active over the last two years while helping care for an elderly relative.\n\nAbout three months ago, {patientName} noticed a firm lump in the left breast while showering but initially assumed it was benign because it was only mildly uncomfortable. When the lump persisted and seemed more defined, she saw her primary clinician, prompting imaging and biopsy. She denies fevers or infectious symptoms. She reports increased anxiety, reduced sleep, and occasional nausea around appointments, but no frank functional decline. She is motivated to pursue treatment and has strong support from her spouse and adult daughter."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
